        &nbsp;<a href="post.asp?method=ReplyQuote&REPLY_ID=35260&TOPIC_ID=4687&FORUM_ID=1&CAT_ID=1&Forum_Title=General+Discussions&Topic_Title=Pets+and+Experience&M="><img src="icon_reply_topic.gif" height=15 width=15 alt="Reply with Quote" border="0" align="absmiddle" hspace="6"></a>


        <hr noshade size="1">
        
        <font color="white" face="Verdana, Arial, Helvetica" size="2"><BLOCKQUOTE id=quote><font size=1 face="Verdana, Arial, Helvetica" id=quote>quote:<hr height=1 noshade id=quote></P><P>How does seq, or anything else for that matter show who has acquired the most hate.</P><P><hr height=1 noshade id=quote></BLOCKQUOTE id=quote></font id=quote><font face="Verdana, Arial, Helvetica" size=2 id=quote></P><P>There is no way to tell, however you can do some poor-granularity tests on hate creation by having players of similiar level standing on a mobs toes during a fight to mitigate the filtering factors like distance.</P><P><BR><BLOCKQUOTE id=quote><font size=1 face="Verdana, Arial, Helvetica" id=quote>quote:<hr height=1 noshade id=quote><BR>There must be at least 2 values involved with mob-player interaction.  Hate, which is acrued based upon damage, debuff, taunting, distance to player, player sitting down, and which is evident from which char the mob is trying to beat down.  And Damage, which seems to be primarily concerned with determining who gets the exp.<BR><hr height=1 noshade id=quote></BLOCKQUOTE id=quote></font id=quote><font face="Verdana, Arial, Helvetica" size=2 id=quote></P><P>There is only Hate value (innoruuk would be proud). The choice of who a mob attacks next is filtered through several things like distance, respective level, frenzy factor, etc.</P><P>Sitting and dropping low on health do not create hate, they simplify magnify it.</P><P><BLOCKQUOTE id=quote><font size=1 face="Verdana, Arial, Helvetica" id=quote>quote:<hr height=1 noshade id=quote><BR>It doesn't seem right to think that hate would come into play for exp determination in only the one special instance where you are grouped and have a pet.  <BR><hr height=1 noshade id=quote></BLOCKQUOTE id=quote></font id=quote><font face="Verdana, Arial, Helvetica" size=2 id=quote></P><P>Why not? Personally, I think the way it is implemented, within the limits of the hatelist management system they have, is "fair," if not desireable for pet classes.</P><P>It's no more or less broken than how experience is award in multigroup battles with Dragons and the like, where a single player who did relatively minor damage would get the will award simply by renewing a debuff or somesuch towards the end of a fight.</P><P>I don't believe EQ has any sort of "absolute damage" counter in a fight. Let's say, for instance, that a mob has 100 hp. Player 1 beats it up for 75, then runs out of aggro range. Some time later, Player 2 wacks it for 80, then runs out of aggro range. Some time later, Players 3 and 4 do 51 and 49 damage to it, respectively, and kill it.</P><P>Who gets the kill credit? Player 3, because that was who the mob hated the most when it died. This is why hatelist wiping with ST or mem blur works for powerleveling people, and why you can make a corpse poof by DOTing and successfully FDing.</P><P></P><P>-- <BR>Life is a zero sum game, the only way to win is not to play.<a href="#top"><img src="icon_go_up.gif" height=15 width=15 border="0" align="right" alt="Go to Top of Page"></a></font></td>
